As you can see in the pictures, a long chamber Krink style flash hider was spot welded on the barrel end to make it legal length of 16 inches. The Underfolder is tight and locks up in both positions very nicely! If you choose to legally SBR it, all that is needed would be a 1 minute grind with a dermal of the small spot weld to remove it. It is a genuine M92 Krinkov Yugo factory virgin kit that was put together on a correct 1.5mm Nodak Spuds M92 Krink Receiver by Red Jacket Firearms (top pic when I got it back from them)! I have ONLY fired two 30 round mags through it sense I had it built by Red Jacket just to test it out! All 60 rounds fired wonderfully without any problems at all!! It has a deep base sound unlike any other AK when fired. This is an awesome AK and truly one of a kind, it is unmatched in quality hands down! These are collector item Krinkov AK-47s that are very hard to come by! Virgin Kits alone will run you $800-$900 without a receiver and build costs for in stock sites (if you can find one at all)! As you can see in the picture with a Romanian WASR 10/63 the Krinkov (top) is absolutely a beautiful work of art for an AK. title: For Sale:  Kimber 1911 "Detachment-One"
postcontent:
I have one New-in-Box/Never Fired, Kimber Marine Corps Special
Operations Command, Detachment One (MCSOCOM Det-1) 1911 pistol
for sale. These were specially made and procured for MCSOCOM Det-1
upon the unit's activation in June 2003. The unit was eventually disbanded
before Marine Corps Forces Special Operations Command (MARSOC)
activation in 2006, and Kimber offered members of the unit an
opportunity to buy a few through Kimber before being deactivated.
Approximately 375 of these pistols were ever produced and roughly 110
of them still remain in the USMC arsenal, the rest were sold to the
members of the unit. This is one of the rarest 1911 pistols ever produced.
This has the "DET1-3XX" (serial numbers) and "US Military Property
USMC" markings on them. "NO OTHER" 1911 in history has "EVER"
been produced and stamped with "US Military Property USMC" markings
on them and on top of that, this was a very small production run. Look it
up and research it for yourself, these already are hard to find (especially
NIB/NF condition) and sought after by serious gun collectors. You can
confirm that these are authentic by contacting Kimber. Per Kimber, this
one was manufactured 3/30/2006. You'll get the pistol + 1 Kimber
magazine, 1 authentic colored patch, an extra set of Black Gunner G-10
grips, original Kimber case with the “USMC” and “DET-1” stickers with
matching serial number on the case, and the unit letter from the Base
Commander at Camp Pendleton. This one is considered “factory correct”,
meaning that it does not have the added Dawson rail. Not $12,500.00
Not $10K, Not $7500.00, Not $5K   Asking $4500.00

postcontent:
I've found myself with too many general purpose carbines, so I'm letting this one go. It has a modest appx 3000 round count, having been through two 2-day Basic Carbine courses, and has never had so much as a hiccup. It has been run hard at class, but never abused in any way. For those who know LWRCI rifles, 3000 rounds is barely breaking the gun in, as the barrels have a 20,000+ round life expectancy. This rifle comes completely ready to go for any tactical or defensive use, missing only an optic.

FYI, this is an older generation rifle with the two piece BCG. Included is a complete second BCG, so you need not ever worry about upgrading or damage to the primary BCG, though I cannot find evidence of an LWRC BCG failing.

Upgrades and extras included:
Standard (not OTB mod) complete 2-piece BCG
Spare Piston Spring
Samson Evolution 15" rail
Samson Evolution Sling mount
Tactical Link Z-360 rear sling mount
VTAC wide padded sling
Magpul AFG 1st generation, stippled
Magpul MOE pistol grip, stippled
Magpul MBUS
IWC Drop Wing Scout Light mount
Surefire M600C Scout Light with pushbutton tailcap

Again, no optic or magazines are included. Everything you see in the pictures (except the magazine) is included. Also, the Team America patch has been replaced with a green and black US flag patch. This was added to the rail after the first class, as my grip position is right over the gas block and got quite hot. The patch gives an insulated point of contact for those using more of a c-clamp grip.

With a base asking price of only $1900, additional upgrades to this gun add up to a total of just over $2900. I'm asking $2200 face to face through an FFL in Northern Virginia. If anyone has any questions, please send me a message.
